Don't take this to be arguementative.  It is a good book but . . .<br><br>
I served in Herbert's battalion.  The book has many inaccuracies in it and of course is self-serving.  Tony Herbert was an outstanding combat leader and you couldn't find a better man to be with in a tight situation.  IMO he was screwed by the Army.  He was a hard charger that wanted to kill VC/NVA at a time when the politicians wanted to increase ARVN participation in the war AND (at least superficially) reduce American casualities.  Herberts tactics did neither.  But they worked.<br><br>
Still the Colonel twists the truth to sell his book.  Anti-war sentiments sold back in the early 70s, and who can blame him for wanting to hurt back the Army who had betrayed him.<br><br>
Enjoy the book but remember its slanted and not everything he claims is true.<br><br>
